ery image 1","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 1"},{"id":3,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-36-31.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 1","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 1"},{"id":4,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsanbawi.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 2","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 2"},{"id":5,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/photo-001.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 3","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 3"},{"id":6,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-gwongumseong-cable-car.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 4","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 4"},{"id":7,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsan-rock.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 5","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 5"},{"id":8,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-05.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 2","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 2"},{"id":9,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-12-05.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 3","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 3"},{"id":10,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/nami-metasequoia-sunset-lake.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 6","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 6"},{"id":11,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-43-58.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 2","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 2"},{"id":12,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/garden-of-morning-calm-flowers.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 3","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 3"},{"id":13,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-09-33.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 4","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 4"}],"itineraryStops":[{"name":"Pickup (Hongik University Station or Myeongdong Station)","time":"06:00 / 06:30","number":1,"category":"Coach pickup","duration":"30 min window","timeUsed":["Arrive at your chosen pickup point 5 min before scheduled time (~5 min)","Identify the AtoC Korea coach at the marked Starbucks/NorthFace front (~5 min)","Board large coach in pickup queue (~10 min)","Printed Korean-English itinerary card distributed at boarding"],"whyOnRoute":"Two early pickup points cover Seoul''s two major hotel/hostel clusters: Hongik University area (Mapo-gu, popular with younger travelers and short-stay guests) and Myeongdong (Jung-gu, the legacy tourist district near the Lotte/Shilla/Westin hotels). Departure at 06:00 from Hongik or 06:30 from Myeongdong is the earliest practical pickup that still respects Seoul subway operating hours (Line 2 starts ~05:30) — and is the only way to arrive at Seoraksan before 10:00 for a meaningful 3-hour park visit. Hongik first, Myeongdong second is the natural northeast-bound route via Olympic Expressway → Seoul-Yangyang Expressway.","description":"Pickup is at one of two Seoul meeting points: **(1) Starbucks Hongik University Station Exit 8 (Mapo-gu)** at 06:00 — the Starbucks storefront is immediately at the top of Exit 8 with seating until 22:00 the night before if you need shelter from cold weather; OR **(2) Myeongdong Station Exit 2 (Jung-gu)** at 06:30 — the NorthFace flagship store is the visible landmark adjacent to the exit. \n\nBoth pickup points share the same large coach, and Hongik passengers board first. Please be at your chosen pickup point **5 minutes before scheduled time** for the on-time departure — the 13-hour itinerary depends on arriving at Seoraksan before 10:00. Driver-guide distributes a printed Korean-English itinerary card at boarding and confirms the day''s running order, restroom stops, and the typical 19:00 return time. \n\nFrom Myeongdong (final pickup point), the coach takes the Olympic Expressway east, then transitions to the Seoul-Yangyang Expressway for the ~2.5-hour drive to Seoraksan."},{"name":"Seoraksan National Park","time":"≈ 10:00","number":2,"category":"National Park (Mountain)","duration":"180 min (3 hours)","timeUsed":["Arrival at Seorakdong Entrance + driver-guide orientation (~10 min)","Walk to Tongildaebul + Sinheungsa Temple (~15-20 min from main parking)","Optional cable car to Gwongeumseong (~30-45 min including queue) OR Biseondae walk (~90 min)","Photo time + reassembly at vehicle (~15 min)","Optional 800-year-old Pine Tree photo stop near Sinheungsa (~5 min)"],"_poi_meta":{"poi_key":"seoraksan_national_park","verified":true,"match":"single_poi","kb_version":"1.27","verified_date":"2026-04-29","sources":["Korea Tourism Organization (VisitKorea — Seoraksan National Park (Outer Seorak) listing + IUCN Green List confirmation)","IUCN Green List of Protected and Conserved Areas (iucngreenlist.org — Seoraksan official entry + 2014 designation + 398.24 km² area)","Korea National Park Service (KNPS — Seoraksan National Park Office official site + endangered species management plan)","UNESCO World Heritage Centre (Mt. Sorak Biosphere Reserve 1982 designation + tentative World Heritage listing)","Wikipedia (Seoraksan National Park — corpus on 30 peaks, 2,000+ animal species, 1,400+ plant species)"]},"highlights":["Korea''s 5th national park (1970) and first UNESCO Biosphere Reserve (Aug 1982)","Tongildaebul: 14.6 m / 108 tons bronze — Korea''s largest seated bronze Buddha (1997)","Sinheungsa Temple (652 CE Silla) — one of Korea''s oldest active Buddhist temples and a Jogye Order monastery","Optional Seorak Cable Car 1,132 m to Gwongeumseong Fortress platform (700 m, 1253 legend)","30 peaks, 2,000+ animal species, 1,400-1,562 plant species; rare wildlife (musk deer, goral, Asian black bear)","Park entrance FREE since May 2023 (was 3,500 KRW); cable car still paid","**IUCN Category II (National Park) since 2005 + IUCN Green List of Protected Areas since 2014** — Korea''s first national park to enter the Green List during the Pilot Phase, alongside Odaesan and Jirisan","**Korea''s first UNESCO Biosphere Reserve since August 1982** + **listed as UNESCO World Heritage tentative site** — combined recognition unmatched by any other Korean national park","**Long-tailed goral conservation centerpiece**: stable population of ~260 individuals (vulnerable on IUCN Red List) — the park manages 10 Special Protection Zones covering 39 km² (10% of total park area) for endangered species"],"smartNotes":{"photo":"Tongildaebul (14.6 m bronze Buddha) is the iconic single shot. Cable car ride frames Sinheungsa + Ulsanbawi Rock + Sokcho City + East Sea. October foliage against granite peaks is world-famous.","facilities":"Visitor center, cafes (Dahyang Cafe), restaurants, gift shops at Seorakdong Entrance. Free hiking equipment rental 9:00-14:00 (return by 16:00). Asiatic Black Bear Statue mascot near entrance.","tip":"Cable car tickets ARE NOT bookable in advance — queues can exceed 1-2 hours in October. If skies are foggy, skip the cable car entirely (no view). Best 3-hour budget: Tongildaebul + Sinheungsa + Biseondae streamside walk. Wear sturdy closed-toe shoes — paths are rocky and damp in places."},"whyOnRoute":"The 2.5-hour drive each way is justified only by the centerpiece: Korea''s 5th national park (1970) and the country''s first UNESCO Biosphere Reserve (1982) — combined with the Korea''s largest seated bronze Buddha and the world''s oldest Zen Buddhist temple, all within a 15-minute walk of the Sogongwon entrance. Placing Seoraksan first uses the freshest morning energy on the day''s most physically active stop, with Nami and Morning Calm afterward as flatter walking-and-photography stops. Seoraksan''s combined IUCN Green List + UNESCO Biosphere Reserve + tentative World Heritage status makes it **Korea''s most-recognized natural-heritage park** — a credential that helps the day trip earn its 5-hour round-trip drive cost for first-time-Korea travelers seeking a single mountain anchor.","convenience":{"restroom":"At main entrance area, cable car station, Sinheungsa Temple grounds, along major trails","parking":"Available at Sogongwon main entrance (paid)"},"description":"Seoraksan was Korea''s 5th national park — designated March 1970 — and remains the country''s first UNESCO Biosphere Reserve, recognized in August 1982 for its exceptional mountain biodiversity. \n\nThe park spans approximately 398 km² across four cities and counties, with 30 named peaks anchored by Daecheongbong (1,708 m, Korea''s 3rd highest peak) and the famous six-pillared granite formation of Ulsanbawi Rock. Park entrance is FREE since the May 2023 abolition of the 3,500-KRW fee that was historically collected on behalf of Sinheungsa Temple — now public funds maintain the temple instead. \n\nFrom the Sogongwon (Outer Seorak / Oeseorak) main entrance, the typical 3-hour visit covers three highlights: the **Tongildaebul (Great Unification Buddha)** — at 14.6 m and 108 tons of bronze, the Korea''s largest seated bronze Buddha, erected 1997 in prayer for Korean reunification, with a small Bodhisattva Guan Yin shrine inside its base; **Sinheungsa Temple** itself, founded 652 by Jajangyulsa during the Silla Kingdom and considered the one of Korea''s oldest active Buddhist temples plus a Jogye Order temple; and the optional **Seorak Cable Car** (1,132 m travel distance, ~10 min one-way to the 700 m Gwongeumseong Fortress platform — round-trip Adult 16,000 KRW / Child 12,000 KRW, on-site ticketing only, no advance reservation, often hours-long queues during October autumn-foliage peak). \n\nGwongeumseong Fortress at the top carries a vivid legend: erected in a single day during the 1253 Mongolian invasion of the Goryeo Dynasty by two generals named Kwon and Kim — hence Gwon-geum-seong. Active hikers who skip the cable car can instead choose the easy 1.5 km Biseondae Rock streamside walk (paved most of the way), the Heundeulbawi ''rocking rock'' loop (1.5 hr each way with stone steps), or the 600 m Geumganggul Cave climb (~1hr 40 min round trip).","visitBasics":{"hours":"Park always open; Cable car typically 08:00-17:30 (weather-dependent); Sinheungsa Temple 06:00-sunset","closed":"Open year-round; some trails may close periodically for restoration","admission":"Park entrance FREE (was 3,500 KRW until May 2023 abolition); Cable car RT Adult 16,000 / Child 12,000 KRW (on-site only, no advance booking; NOT included in this tour)","walking":"Easy paths at base (Sinheungsa, cable-car base); moderate to challenging hikes (Biseondae 3 km, Ulsanbawi steep stairs, Heundeulbawi 1.5 hr each way)"},"image":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-ridge-view.webp","images":["/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-ridge-view.webp","/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsanbawi.webp","/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/photo-001.webp","/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-gwongumseong-cable-car.webp","/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsan-rock.webp"],"imageCredits":[{"url":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-ridge-view.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsanbawi.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/photo-001.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-gwongumseong-cable-car.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsan-rock.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/photo-001.webp","source":"atoc-korea"}],"galleryItems":[{"id":1,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-ridge-view.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 1","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 1"},{"id":2,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsanbawi.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 2","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 2"},{"id":3,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/photo-001.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 3","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 3"},{"id":4,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-gwongumseong-cable-car.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 4","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 4"},{"id":5,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/seoraksan-national-park/seoraksan-sinheungsa-ulsan-rock.webp","location":"Seoraksan National Park","caption":"Seoraksan National Park — photo 5","alt":"Seoraksan National Park — gallery image 5"}]},{"name":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","time":"≈ 14:30","number":3,"category":"Ferry-Access Island & K-Drama Landmark","duration":"120 min (2 hours)","timeUsed":["Ferry crossing from Gapyeong Wharf (5-10 minutes including queue)","Free walking time along the Metasequoia / Ginkgo / Korean Pine avenues — half-island circuit ~3 km","Optional bicycle rental (single 7,000 / tandem 14,000 KRW per hour) or electric blue train (3,000 KRW one-way to UNICEF Hall)","Quick on-island snack pause (Sonata Cafe, hotteok, sweet potato latte)","Return ferry to the mainland"],"_poi_meta":{"poi_key":"nami_island","verified":true,"match":"single_poi","kb_version":"1.27","verified_date":"2026-04-29","sources":["Korea Tourism Organization (VisitKorea — Nami Island official listing + visa fee schedule)","Naminara Republic Official Site (namisum-en.imweb.me — own corpus on cultural-independence brand)","UNICEF Korea (Nami Island 2010 Child Friendly Park designation + International Children''s Book Festival)","KBS / Korea Times (Winter Sonata 2002 production retrospectives + Japanese tourism boom coverage)","Wikipedia (Namiseom — open corpus on General Nami history + Cheongpyeong Dam 1944 origin)"]},"highlights":["Half-moon river island, ~460,000 m² / 5 km circumference; named after General Nami (1441-1468)","Iconic Metasequoia tree-lined avenue — Winter Sonata (2002) signature filming location","Self-declared ''Naminara Republic'' since 2006 — own flag, currency, passport (tourism concept)","5-min ferry from Gapyeong Wharf (08:00-21:00, every 10-20 min during peak)","On-island wildlife: peacocks (incl. rare albino), ostriches, wild rabbits, squirrels","**Land formed in 1944** when the Japanese-built Cheongpyeong Dam raised the Bukhan River","**UNICEF Child Friendly Park designation 2010** + Nami Island Arts & Education hosts **600+ performances/exhibitions/festivals annually**"],"smartNotes":{"photo":"Metasequoia avenue is the world-famous Winter Sonata shot — best in autumn (golden, late October-early November) or winter (snow). Riverside Lover''s Ginkgo Tree Lane on the south side is quieter and equally photogenic. Albino peacock occasionally appears near Lover''s Lane.","facilities":"On-island restaurants serve Korean comfort food (hotteok, sweet potato latte, tteok-galbi). Sonata Cafe in a traditional hanok is the signature stop. Foreign-card-friendly ticket counter at Gapyeong Wharf — ticket machines do not accept foreign cards, ask at the counter.","tip":"Best seasons: spring (April-May cherry blossoms), autumn (October golden ginkgo + red maple), winter (December-February snow-quiet paths reminiscent of Winter Sonata). Avoid the Sunday late-afternoon ferry queue."},"whyOnRoute":"Nami Island comes second after Seoraksan because the **Seoraksan → Nami drive (~2 hours via Inje-Hongcheon-Chuncheon)** lands the coach at Gapyeong Wharf around 14:30 — past the heaviest 11:00-14:00 ferry-line peak and with afternoon side-light still available for the Metasequoia avenue photography. The 2-hour stop allows a comfortable ferry round-trip plus the half-island circuit covering the three tree-lined avenues without rushing. Pairing Nami with Morning Calm in the same afternoon also leverages the **30-minute drive** between them — both are in the Gapyeong/Cheongpyeong corridor that the day''s east-west axis already traverses.","convenience":{"restroom":"Multiple on island and at Gapyeong Wharf","parking":"Gapyeong Wharf 6,000 KRW small car / 10,000 KRW large vehicle"},"description":"Nami Island opens the day''s second chapter with a 5-minute ferry crossing from Gapyeong Wharf onto a half-moon-shaped river island in the Bukhan River. Approximately **460,000 m² (140,000 pyeong) and ~5 km in circumference**, Namiseom is named after **General Nami (Nam Yi, 1441-1468)**, a Joseon-era military commander executed at age 28 after being falsely accused of treason during the reign of King Yejong. \n\nThe island originally became land only during floods; **in 1944 the Japanese colonial government built the Cheongpyeong Dam, raising the river level and making Nami a permanent island**. It found global fame **in 2002 as the filming location for KBS drama ''Winter Sonata''** starring Bae Yong-joon and Choi Ji-woo — the catalyst for the early 2000s Hallyu wave — and continues to draw about **3.3 million visitors annually (1.3 million foreign)**, making it Korea''s most-visited single tourist destination after Seoul, Busan, and Jeju. \n\nSince **March 1, 2006** the island has branded itself as the self-declared **''Naminara Republic''** with its own flag, currency (Nami Tongbo coins), passport, and postal service — a tourism marketing concept rather than an actual political entity. \n\nThe signature **Metasequoia tree-lined avenue** (Winter Sonata''s iconic snowy lane), the **Riverside Lover''s Ginkgo Tree Lane** on the south side, the **Korean Pine Road**, and the recycled-glass **Sequoia Bridge** made from soju bottles are all walkable in a relaxed two hours. On-island wildlife includes peacocks (including rare albinos), ostriches, wild rabbits, and squirrels. \n\n**The Naminara Republic VISA Fee (round-trip ferry included) is included in this tour price**.","visitBasics":{"hours":"Island 08:00-21:00 (last ferry varies); on-island shops mostly close by 18:00","closed":"Open year-round","admission":"Naminara Republic VISA Fee (round-trip ferry included): Adult 19,000 KRW — INCLUDED in this tour","walking":"Easy — flat tree-lined paths; half-perimeter walk ~3 km; full perimeter ~5 km. Bicycle / e-buggy rental available for low-mobility visitors."},"image":"/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-04.webp","images":["/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-04.webp","/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-05.webp","/images/tours/nami-island/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-12-05.webp","/images/tours/nami-island/nami-metasequoia-sunset-lake.webp"],"imageCredits":[{"url":"/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-04.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-05.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/nami-island/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-12-05.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/nami-island/nami-metasequoia-sunset-lake.webp","source":"atoc-korea"}],"galleryItems":[{"id":1,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-04.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 1","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 1"},{"id":2,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/kakaotalk-20260510-222949305-05.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 2","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 2"},{"id":3,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-12-05.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 3","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 3"},{"id":4,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/nami-island/nami-metasequoia-sunset-lake.webp","location":"Nami Island (Namiseom)","caption":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — photo 6","alt":"Nami Island (Namiseom) — gallery image 6"}]},{"name":"The Garden of Morning Calm","time":"≈ 17:00","number":4,"category":"Themed Botanical Garden","duration":"70 min","timeUsed":["Garden entry and brief orientation by the driver-guide (~5 min)","Free walking time across the 20 themed sub-gardens (~50 min)","Optional Sunken Garden (Korean Peninsula shape) extended photo time (~10 min)","Winter visits: arrival timed for 17:00 illumination start to see daytime garden + lighting festival ignition","Reassemble at coach (~5 min)"],"_poi_meta":{"poi_key":"garden_of_morning_calm","verified":true,"match":"single_poi","kb_version":"1.27","verified_date":"2026-04-29","sources":["Garden of Morning Calm Official Site (morningcalm.co.kr — own corpus on founder + 1996 opening + 20 sub-gardens)","Korea Tourism Organization (VisitKorea — Lighting Festival listing + lighting-fest schedule)","Gyeonggi Cultural Foundation (ggc.ggcf.kr — official cultural promotion entry on Sunken Garden + 200,000 LEDs)","Sahmyook University Department of Horticulture (Prof. Han Sang-kyung honorary professor profile + garden origin)","Wikipedia (Garden of Morning Calm — corpus on Tagore-derived name + 5,000 species + 330,000 m² total)"]},"highlights":["Korea''s signature private arboretum — 330,000 m² with ~5,000 plant species","Founded by Han Sang-kyung of Sahmyook University; opened 1996 (conceived 1992)","Winter Lighting Festival December - March with 200,000+ LEDs (Korea''s first natural-environment light festival)","20 themed sub-gardens — Sunken Garden shaped like the Korean peninsula, Moonlight Garden, Bonsai Garden, Garden of Eden","K-drama filming location for Moonlight Drawn by Clouds and others","**Conceived 1992 / land purchased 1994 / opened May 11, 1996**: Founder Prof. Han Sang-kyung and his wife designed and personally cultivated the entire garden, even selling their house during early financial hardship","**Selected by CNN as one of Korea''s Top 50 Tourist Attractions** — the Sunken Garden''s Korean Peninsula shape (10 large/small flower beds expressing yearning for unification) is the CNN-cited landmark feature","**Cheonnyeonhyang (Chinese juniper)** is the official symbol of Morning Calm — the garden''s signature plant species among the 5,000 total catalogued"],"smartNotes":{"photo":"Spring (cherry blossoms April), summer (lush greens), autumn (foliage October-early November), and winter (lighting festival post-sunset) all photograph differently. The light tunnels at dusk during festival period are the iconic shot.","facilities":"Food Garden serves Korean comfort food (soybean-paste stew, vegetable bibimbap, snow cheese tteokbokki). Good Morning Coffee in a hanok roasting house is the signature cafe. Restaurants close at 20:00.","tip":"For the lighting festival (Dec 5 - Mar 15), the 17:00 arrival catches both daytime garden colours and the illumination ignition. Heavy snow February gives the most magical Frozen-movie scene."},"whyOnRoute":"Morning Calm closes the day with its calmest visual chapter, ~30 minutes south of Nami Island. The 17:00 arrival aligns perfectly with the **Winter Lighting Festival illumination ignition (December 5 - March 15)** — guests effectively pay one entry fee but experience two distinct visual gardens (daytime arboretum + night LED festival). In non-festival months, the same 17:00 window captures the **transitional afternoon light** that the garden''s photography reputation depends on. The 70-minute stop is intentionally compact — enough for the Sunken Garden, Moonlight Garden, and one or two other themed sub-gardens — and respects the day''s 19:00 Seoul-return target.","convenience":{"restroom":"Multiple, signposted","parking":"Large free coach parking; coin lockers 1,500-2,000 KRW (500-KRW coins only)"},"description":"About 30 minutes south of Nami Island, the Garden of Morning Calm is **Korea''s signature private arboretum** — approximately **330,000 m²** of curated landscape with around **5,000 plant species**. Conceived in **1992** and opened to the public in **1996**, the garden was designed and personally cultivated by **Han Sang-kyung of Sahmyook University**, who at one point sold his house to fund the project; the name draws from Korea''s longstanding nickname ''**Land of the Morning Calm**'' (Joseon). \n\n**Twenty themed sub-gardens** — including the **Sunken Garden shaped like the Korean peninsula**, the Hometown House Garden, the Bonsai Garden, the Moonlight Garden, the Sky Path, and the Garden of Eden — each carry their own visual identity and have served as filming sets for many K-dramas including **Moonlight Drawn by Clouds**. \n\nFrom early December to mid-March every winter, the garden hosts **Korea''s first natural-environment lighting festival** with more than **200,000 environmentally-friendly LED bulbs** covering the grounds, transforming the garden after sunset into a winter wonderland. \n\n**The name ''Garden of Morning Calm''** comes from Indian poet Rabindranath Tagore, who in 1929 referred to Korea as ''the Land of Morning Calm.'' Han Sang-kyung conceived the project in 1992 while serving as exchange professor in the United States, where he was inspired by world-class private gardens. \n\n**Han and his wife designed and personally labored on the garden**, and during periods of financial difficulty they sold their family home and lived in a small dwelling on the garden''s property to continue construction. \n\nThe garden first opened to the public on May 11, 1996, with 10 themed sections; today it has expanded to 20 themed sub-gardens across 330,000 m². **Admission is INCLUDED in this tour price**.","visitBasics":{"hours":"Spring-Autumn 08:30-19:00 (last entry 18:00); Winter Lighting Festival Sun-Fri 11:00-21:00, Sat 11:00-23:00","closed":"Open year-round","admission":"Adult 11,000 KRW — INCLUDED in this tour","walking":"Moderate — extensive paths over rolling terrain through 20 themed sub-gardens; mostly stroller-accessible main loop"},"image":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-36-31.webp","images":["/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-36-31.webp","/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-43-58.webp","/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/garden-of-morning-calm-flowers.webp","/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-09-33.webp"],"imageCredits":[{"url":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-36-31.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-43-58.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/garden-of-morning-calm-flowers.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-09-33.webp","source":"atoc-korea"},{"url":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/garden-of-morning-calm-flowers.webp","source":"atoc-korea"}],"galleryItems":[{"id":1,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-36-31.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 1","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 1"},{"id":2,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-10-10-43-58.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 2","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 2"},{"id":3,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/garden-of-morning-calm-flowers.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 3","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 3"},{"id":4,"type":"photo","src":"/images/tours/garden-of-morning-calm/chatgpt-image-2026-5-11-01-09-33.webp","location":"The Garden of Morning Calm","caption":"The Garden of Morning Calm — photo 4","alt":"The Garden of Morning Calm — gallery image 4"}]},{"name":"Return to Seoul (Hongik University Station or Myeongdong Station)","time":"≈ 19:00","number":5,"category":"Return drop-off","duration":"60 min drive","timeUsed":["Coach departs Morning Calm (~18:10)","Drive to Seoul via Seoul-Yangyang Expressway (~60 min depending on traffic)","Drop-off at Myeongdong Station Exit 2 (~19:00)","Drop-off at Hongik University Station Exit 8 (~19:30)"],"whyOnRoute":"Return runs in reverse-pickup order: **Myeongdong drop-off first** (~19:00) since it is closer to Morning Calm via the Seoul-Yangyang Expressway, then **Hongik University Station drop-off** (~19:30). The 13-hour tour duration is calibrated around this Myeongdong return time — guests with evening dinner reservations should book for 20:00 or later to allow safety buffer for traffic. Friday/Sunday evenings have heavier expressway traffic and the return can run 30 minutes later — please notify the driver-guide if you have a flight or hard appointment.","description":"After Morning Calm, the coach takes the **Seoul-Yangyang Expressway** westbound back into Seoul. Drop-offs are sequenced: **Myeongdong Station Exit 2 first at approximately 19:00**, then **Hongik University Station Exit 8 at approximately 19:30**. \n\nBoth drop-off points are at the same locations as morning pickup. Guests connecting to evening shows in Hongdae or dinner reservations in Myeongdong should plan for **20:00 or later** to allow a comfortable buffer for traffic, particularly on Friday and Sunday evenings when the expressway runs heavier."}],"routeFlowStops":[{"name":"Pickup (Hongik / Myeongdong)","type":"origin","theme":"Seoul pickup"},{"name":"Seoraksan National Park","type":"primary","theme":"Mountain & temple"},{"name":"Nami Island","type":"primary","theme":"K-drama island"},{"name":"The Garden of Morning Calm","type":"primary","theme":"Themed garden"},{"name":"Return to Seoul","type":"return","theme":"Drop-off"}],"routePhases":[{"phase":"Seoul → Seoraksan","duration":"≈ 3 hours","description":"Pickup at 06:00 Hongik / 06:30 Myeongdong, then ~2.5-hour drive northeast via Seoul-Yangyang Expressway to arrive Seoraksan by 10:00."},{"phase":"Seoraksan","duration":"≈ 3 hours","description":"Sogongwon entrance: Tongildaebul, Sinheungsa Temple, and optional cable car to Gwongeumseong or Biseondae streamside walk."},{"phase":"Seoraksan → Nami (incl. lunch)","duration":"≈ 2.5 hours","description":"Drive south via Inje-Hongcheon-Chuncheon corridor; lunch stop at a local Gangwon restaurant en route (own expense)."},{"phase":"Nami Island","duration":"≈ 2 hours","description":"Ferry round-trip and Metasequoia / Ginkgo / Korean Pine avenues walking circuit on Naminara Republic."},{"phase":"Morning Calm & return","duration":"≈ 2 hours","description":"30-min drive south to the Garden of Morning Calm (70-min visit), then 1-hour return to Seoul via Seoul-Yangyang Expressway."}],"routeShapeIntro":{"title":"How this Seoul day moves","subtitle":"Early Hongik/Myeongdong pickup at 06:00/06:30; ~2.5 hr northeast drive to Seoraksan for the day''s mountain anchor; back through the Inje-Chuncheon corridor for Nami Island''s tree-lined ferry circuit; 30-min south to Morning Calm for the day''s gentlest closing chapter (lighting-festival ignition in winter); return to Seoul by 19:00-19:30."},"whyTourWorks":{"bestFor":["First-time visitors to Korea wanting Korea''s three signature day-trip stops in one day","Couples and Hallyu fans visiting for the Winter Sonata Metasequoia avenue","Photography enthusiasts wanting the mountain + island + garden trifecta","Travelers comfortable with a 13-hour day for maximum coverage from a Seoul base"],"lessIdealFor":["Travelers who want a slow-paced single-stop experience","Guests who don''t want to commit to a 13-hour day from a 06:00 start","Young children (under 6) who may struggle with the long coach time","Mobility-limited travelers — Seoraksan paths have stairs and rocky sections"],"routeLogicSections":[{"title":"Pacing & geography","icon":"sun","iconBg":"bg-amber-50/80","iconColor":"text-amber-600","items":[{"label":"Northeast first, west on return","detail":"Seoraksan is the farthest stop (2.5 hr drive each way) so it''s visited first while energy is freshest, with Nami and Morning Calm sequenced on the natural return route through the Chuncheon-Gapyeong corridor — no backtracking."},{"label":"Mountain → island → garden","detail":"The day moves from highest energy (Seoraksan stairs and optional cable car) to medium (Nami''s flat walking circuit) to lowest (Morning Calm''s relaxed garden stroll). Photo style progresses from granite ridge → tree-lined lanes → curated botanical compositions."},{"label":"Winter wonder bonus","detail":"From December 5 - March 15, the Morning Calm 17:00 arrival catches the daytime garden plus the Lighting Festival ignition — 200,000+ LEDs across the 330,000 m² grounds, a single-ticket value most independent travelers can''t time as cleanly."}]},{"title":"Why this works in 13 hours","icon":"clock","iconBg":"bg-pink-50/80","iconColor":"text-pink-600","items":[{"label":"All admissions included","detail":"Nami Island ferry (₩19,000) and Morning Calm garden (₩11,000) are bundled into the tour price — no per-stop tickets needed. Only the optional Seorak Cable Car (₩16,000 round-trip) is on-site own-expense."},{"label":"Two pickup points across Seoul","detail":"Hongik (Mapo-gu) at 06:00 and Myeongdong (Jung-gu) at 06:30 cover Seoul''s two main accommodation clusters — guests choose the exit closest to their hotel."},{"label":"Mostly outdoor stops","detail":"All three stops are predominantly outdoor; the coach is the only indoor segment. Works well in moderate weather; heavy rain shifts cable car off the menu but everything else remains visitable."}]},{"title":"Trade-offs honestly","icon":"info","iconBg":"bg-sky-50/80","iconColor":"text-sky-600","items":[{"label":"Seoraksan has stairs (cable car is optional)","detail":"The Sinheungsa Temple level and the optional Heundeulbawi loop both have stairs. The Tongildaebul + Sinheungsa walk is flat and accessible; the cable car ascent is by chair lift (no stairs in cable car itself), but Gwongeumseong platform has rocky steps at the top."},{"label":"Cable car is not bookable in advance","detail":"Seorak Cable Car tickets are on-site only and can queue 1-2 hours in October peak. If skies are foggy or queues are long, the recommended alternative is the Biseondae streamside walk (flat, paved, ~90 min round trip) which fits the same 3-hour budget."},{"label":"Long day from a 06:00 start","detail":"This is a coach group tour — 13 hours total including ~4.5 hours of coach time. Guests wanting fewer hours or unlimited stop time should consider our private chartered car day trip (door-of-hotel pickup, customizable timing)."}]}]},"practicalAccordionItems":[{"id":"pickup","title":"Pickup & drop-off","preview":"Two Seoul pickup points: Starbucks Hongik University Station Exit 8 at 06:00…","content":["Two Seoul pickup points: **Starbucks Hongik University Station Exit 8 at 06:00** (Mapo-gu), and **Myeongdong Station Exit 2 (NorthFace flagship) at 06:30** (Jung-gu).","Both pickups share the same coach; please be at your chosen point 5 minutes early.","Return drop-offs in reverse order: **Myeongdong ~19:00, Hongik ~19:30**.","Friday/Sunday evenings may run 30 min later due to expressway traffic — notify the guide if you have a hard schedule."]},{"id":"what-to-bring","title":"What to wear & bring","preview":"Comfortable closed-toe walking shoes for Seoraksan paths (rocky in places)…","content":["Comfortable closed-toe walking shoes for Seoraksan paths (rocky in places).","Warm layers October-March; Seoraksan altitude is 5-7°C colder than Seoul.","Camera or smartphone (Nami Metasequoia avenue and Morning Calm are the photo highlights).","Cash and card for lunch (~₩10,000-15,000) and optional Seorak Cable Car (₩16,000) if you plan to ride.","Light snacks if you start without breakfast — first food stop is around 13:00-13:30 en route to Nami."]},{"id":"weather-policy","title":"Weather policy","preview":"Year-round operation.","content":["Year-round operation.","Light rain: tour runs as scheduled — Nami and Morning Calm both have charm in rain; Seoraksan''s lower paths remain walkable with grip shoes.","Heavy rain: Seorak Cable Car typically suspended in storm conditions (refunded if pre-paid); the guide will steer guests to the Biseondae walk or extended Sinheungsa visit instead.","Typhoon-level weather or expressway closure: full refund or rebooking offered."]},{"id":"inclusions","title":"What''s included","preview":"Two Seoul pickups, large coach, English-speaking guide, Nami and Morning Calm admissions…","content":["Two Seoul pickup points and same drop-off points, air-conditioned large coach, licensed English-speaking guide.","**Nami Island ferry round-trip + Naminara Republic VISA Fee (₩19,000) — INCLUDED**.","**The Garden of Morning Calm admission (₩11,000) — INCLUDED**.","**Seoraksan National Park entrance — FREE (abolished May 2023)**.","**NOT included**: lunch en route (~₩10,000-15,000), optional Seorak Cable Car (₩16,000 round-trip, on-site ticketing only)."]},{"id":"language","title":"Language","preview":"Primary tour language: English.","content":["Primary tour language: English.","Chinese-speaking guide available on request — book 3+ days ahead.","Korean spoken throughout the day for menus, signage, and stall interactions; the guide handles translation."]},{"id":"walking","title":"Walking & terrain","preview":"Moderate.","content":["Moderate.","Seoraksan: easy at Sinheungsa Temple base; moderate on the Biseondae walk; challenging if you choose Heundeulbawi or Ulsanbawi (stairs).","Nami Island: flat, paved tree-lined avenues; ~3 km in 2 hours is the typical pace.","Morning Calm: rolling terrain, mostly paved garden paths.","Total walking ≈4-5 km plus the optional Seoraksan stairs.","Strollers viable at Nami and partially at Morning Calm; not at Seoraksan upper trails."]},{"id":"lunch","title":"Lunch (own expense)","preview":"Lunch is taken en route from Seoraksan to Nami, around 13:30…","content":["Lunch is taken en route from Seoraksan to Nami, around 13:30 at a local restaurant in the Inje-Chuncheon corridor.","Typical choices: Chuncheon dakgalbi (the region''s most-famous dish — sweet-spicy stir-fried chicken with cabbage and rice cakes), kalguksu (knife-cut noodle soup), or bibimbap (~₩10,000-15,000).","Vegetarian and halal-friendly options possible with advance notice — please notify at booking."]},{"id":"cancellation","title":"Cancellation","preview":"Free cancellation up to 24 hours before pickup.","content":["Free cancellation up to 24 hours before pickup.","Inside 24 hours: 50% refund.","No-show or missed pickup: no refund — but contact AtoC Korea operations within 10 minutes of pickup time and the coach may briefly wait if running ahead of schedule."]}],"practicalWeatherStatic":{"today":{"temp":"—","label":"See seasonal notes"},"tomorrow":{"temp":"—","label":"See seasonal notes"},"_seasonalSummary":"Seoul + Gangwon: temperate four-season climate. Seoraksan is 5-7°C cooler than Seoul year-round. Hot humid summers (Jun-Aug), crisp cold winters (Dec-Feb), with prime seasons in spring (April cherry blossoms) and autumn (October-November foliage)."},"seasonalVariations":[{"season":"Spring (Mar-May)","description":"Cherry blossoms at Nami Island and Morning Calm in early-mid April; Seoraksan azaleas and forsythia bloom late April. Most comfortable temperature for the long coach day."},{"season":"Summer (Jun-Aug)","description":"Lush green Seoraksan trails; Nami''s tree-lined avenues at peak shade. July monsoon may shorten Seoraksan time. Morning Calm''s hydrangeas and roses peak in June."},{"season":"Autumn (Sep-Nov)","description":"Korea''s signature season — Seoraksan foliage mid-October to early November is world-famous; Nami''s ginkgo and metasequoia gold in late October-November; Morning Calm''s chrysanthemum and maple in October. Highest demand — book 2+ weeks ahead."},{"season":"Winter (Dec-Feb)","description":"**Winter is the signature ''Winter Wonder'' season for this tour**: Seoraksan snow on granite peaks; Nami''s snowy Metasequoia avenue evokes the Winter Sonata visual identity; Morning Calm''s Winter Lighting Festival (Dec 5 - Mar 15) lights 200,000+ LEDs across the gardens — visiting at the tour''s 17:00 arrival catches both daytime garden colours and the illumination ignition."}],"bookingTrustItems":[{"icon":"check-circle","title":"All admissions included","description":"Nami ferry + Morning Calm bundled","iconBg":"bg-emerald-50/80","iconColor":"text-emerald-600","body":"Nami Island ferry (₩19,000) and Garden of Morning Calm (₩11,000) admissions are pre-paid into the tour price — no per-stop ticket queues. Seoraksan entrance is FREE (abolished May 2023). Total admission savings: ~₩30,000."},{"icon":"users","title":"Licensed English-speaking guide","description":"Korea-licensed tour guide","iconBg":"bg-pink-50/80","iconColor":"text-pink-600","body":"Korea Tourism Organization-licensed guide with English fluency; Chinese-speaking guide available on advance request. Guide narration covers Seoraksan''s Silla-era temple history, Nami''s Winter Sonata legacy, and Morning Calm''s founder story."},{"icon":"shield","title":"Transparent pricing","description":"No hidden shopping stops","iconBg":"bg-sky-50/80","iconColor":"text-sky-600","body":"No ginseng shops, no duty-free, no commissioned souvenir detours. Every minute of the 13-hour day is at an attraction or in transit — what you book is what you experience."}],"bookingSupportSteps":[{"timing":"Immediately","title":"Instant Confirmation","detail":"Booking confirmation with pickup point selection","description":"Instant booking confirmation with Hongik/Myeongdong pickup point selection."},{"timing":"Day before","title":"Pickup Details","detail":"Exact pickup location and vehicle info via WhatsApp/SMS","description":"Weather check, coach plate number, and any seasonal route notes (Morning Calm Lighting Festival timing, Seoraksan foliage peak, etc.) sent the day before."},{"timing":"Morning of","title":"Pickup Confirmation","detail":"Guide identification at pickup point 10 min before departure","description":"Guide waits at Starbucks Hongik Exit 8 from 05:50; at Myeongdong Exit 2 (NorthFace) from 06:20. Photo of the guide and coach sent to your WhatsApp the night before."},{"timing":"During tour","title":"On-tour Support","detail":"Guide narration at each stop + 24/7 ops support","description":"Guide provides on-site narration on Seoraksan''s 652 CE Silla-era founding, Nami''s 1944 Cheongpyeong Dam origin + 2002 Winter Sonata legacy, and Morning Calm''s 1992 conception + 1996 opening."},{"timing":"End of day","title":"Two Drop-off Points","detail":"Myeongdong ~19:00 / Hongik ~19:30","description":"Coach drops at both pickup points in reverse order on return."},{"timing":"After tour","title":"Review & Follow-up","detail":"Optional post-tour review","description":"Post-tour feedback request sent; restaurant or attraction recommendations for the rest of your Seoul stay answered same day."}],"staticQuestions":[{"id":"duration","question":"How long is this tour?","answer":"13 hours door-to-door from a 06:00 Hongik or 06:30 Myeongdong pickup. Returns to Seoul between 19:00 (Myeongdong) and 19:30 (Hongik)."},{"id":"pickup","question":"Where exactly is the pickup?","answer":"Two pickup points: (1) **Starbucks Hongik University Station Exit 8** (Mapo-gu) at 06:00 — the Starbucks at the top of the exit; or (2) **Myeongdong Station Exit 2** (Jung-gu) at 06:30 — the NorthFace flagship store at the top of the exit. Choose the one closest to your hotel at booking."},{"id":"drop-off","question":"Where is the drop-off?","answer":"Drop-off is at the same two locations in reverse order: Myeongdong Exit 2 first at approximately 19:00, then Hongik University Exit 8 at approximately 19:30. Friday/Sunday evenings may run 30 minutes later due to expressway traffic."},{"id":"admissions","question":"Are admissions included?","answer":"Yes for the two stops with paid entry: **Nami Island ferry round-trip (₩19,000) and Garden of Morning Calm admission (₩11,000) are INCLUDED**. **Seoraksan National Park entrance is FREE** (the historical 3,500 KRW fee was abolished in May 2023). The **only paid optional item is the Seorak Cable Car** (₩16,000 round-trip) which is on-site ticketing only — own expense."},{"id":"cable-car","question":"Should I ride the Seorak Cable Car?","answer":"It''s a fantastic ridge view if the weather is clear, but tickets are NOT bookable in advance and on-site queues can exceed 1-2 hours during October autumn-foliage peak. If skies are foggy, skip it (no view). The recommended alternative is the **Biseondae streamside walk** (1.5 km paved, ~90 min round trip from the entrance) which fits the same 3-hour Seoraksan budget."},{"id":"winter-sonata","question":"Is Nami the Winter Sonata filming location?","answer":"Yes — Nami Island''s Metasequoia tree-lined avenue is the signature filming location for the 2002 KBS drama ''Winter Sonata'' starring Bae Yong-joon and Choi Ji-woo. The avenue is photogenic in any season, but autumn (golden October-November) and winter (snow-covered) are the most evocative."},{"id":"lighting-festival","question":"Will I see the Morning Calm Lighting Festival?","answer":"Yes if you book between **December 5 - March 15** — the tour''s 17:00 Morning Calm arrival catches the daytime garden plus the illumination ignition. Outside the festival period (April-November), Morning Calm is the day''s most relaxed botanical chapter with seasonal blooms (cherry blossoms April, hydrangeas June, foliage October)."},{"id":"kids","question":"Is this tour suitable for children?","answer":"Yes, age 6 and up. The 13-hour day with a 06:00 start is long for younger children — please consider age 8+ for comfort. Kids tend to enjoy Nami Island''s peacocks and the Sequoia Bridge, plus Morning Calm''s lighting festival in winter. Seoraksan paths have rocky sections but Sinheungsa Temple and the cable car are kid-friendly."},{"id":"seniors","question":"Is this OK for seniors?","answer":"Active seniors are fine — the day''s main physical demands are the 2-3 km walking circuits at Nami and Morning Calm (both flat or rolling). At Seoraksan, the Sinheungsa Temple level is easily accessible; the Heundeulbawi ''rocking rock'' loop requires stairs and is skippable. Mobility-limited travelers should consider our private chartered car day trip instead."},{"id":"lunch","question":"Is lunch included?","answer":"No — lunch is paid by the guest (~₩10,000-15,000 per person). The coach stops at a local Gangwon-do restaurant en route from Seoraksan to Nami around 13:30. Typical local choices: **Chuncheon dakgalbi** (sweet-spicy stir-fried chicken with cabbage and rice cakes), **kalguksu** (knife-cut noodle soup), or bibimbap. Vegetarian and halal-friendly options possible with advance notice."},{"id":"language","question":"What languages does the guide speak?","answer":"English primarily. Chinese-speaking guide available on request — book 3+ days ahead. The guide handles all menu translation and stall interactions during the day."},{"id":"best-season","question":"What''s the best season for this tour?","answer":"**Autumn (mid-October to early November)** is Korea''s signature foliage season — Seoraksan foliage is world-famous and Nami''s ginkgo + maple lanes are peak gold. **Winter (December-March)** is the ''Winter Wonder'' season with Seoraksan snow, Nami''s Winter Sonata atmosphere, and Morning Calm''s Lighting Festival. **Spring (April)** brings cherry blossoms at Nami and Morning Calm. Book 2+ weeks ahead for October."},{"id":"rain","question":"What if it rains?","answer":"Light rain: tour runs as scheduled — all three stops are walkable in rain with the right footwear. Heavy rain: Seorak Cable Car typically suspended (the guide pivots to Biseondae walk); Nami and Morning Calm still operate normally. Typhoon-level weather or expressway closure: full refund or rebooking offered."},{"id":"private","question":"How does this compare to a private chartered tour?","answer":"This is a coach group tour at the budget price point ($59/person). Our **private chartered car day trip** option provides door-of-hotel pickup, flexible timing, customizable route (e.g. add Petite France or drop Seoraksan), and private vehicle for typically $300-450 per group of 4 — comparable per-person at 5+ pax. Choose the coach tour for budget, choose private for flexibility and comfort."},{"id":"walking","question":"How much walking is there?","answer":"Approximately 4-5 km total across the three stops, plus the optional Seoraksan cable car platform stairs if you choose that route. Sturdy closed-toe shoes recommended (Seoraksan paths can be damp or rocky in places)."}],"guestReviews":[],"reviewsSummary":{"averageRating":0,"totalReviews":0,"ratingDistribution":[{"stars":5,"count":0,"percentage":0},{"stars":4,"count":0,"percentage":0},{"stars":3,"count":0,"percentage":0},{"stars":2,"count":0,"percentage":0},{"stars":1,"count":0,"percentage":0}],"highlights":[]},"pickup_dropoff":{"primary":{"name":"Starbucks Hongik University Station Exit 8","address":"Yanghwa-ro, Mapo-gu, Seoul (in front of the Starbucks at Hongik University Station Exit 8)","time":"06:00 pickup / 19:30 drop-off","instructions":"Meet the guide at the Starbucks storefront immediately above Hongik University Station Exit 8. Look for the AtoC Korea sign and the large coach in the pickup queue."},"alternates":[{"name":"Myeongdong Station Exit 2 (NorthFace flagship)","address":"Toegye-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul (NorthFace flagship store at Myeongdong Station Exit 2)","time":"06:30 pickup / 19:00 drop-off","instructions":"Meet the guide in front of the NorthFace flagship store at the top of Myeongdong Station Exit 2."}]},"matching_profile":{"profile_version":6,"is_active":true,"product_id":"seoul-seoraksan-nami-island-morning-calm-day-tour","product_type":"bus","route_type":"fixed_route","destination_region":"seoul_gangwon","region_type":"gangwon_seoraksan","vehicle_type":"large_coach","duration_hours":13,"region_tags":["seoul_mapo","seoul_jung","gangwon_sokcho","gyeonggi_gapyeong"],"theme_tags":["national_park","mountain","buddhist_temple","k_drama_filming","themed_garden","hallyu_landmark"],"poi_tags":["seoraksan_national_park","nami_island","garden_of_morning_calm"],"pace_level":0.7,"walking_level":0.6,"scenic_level":1,"photo_level":1,"culture_level":0.85,"relax_level":0.5,"first_time_fit":1,"family_fit":0.7,"senior_fit":0.6,"couple_fit":1,"solo_traveler_fit":0.9,"active_traveler_fit":0.85,"adult_family_fit":0.95,"family_with_teens_fit":0.95,"young_kids_fit":0.4,"senior_active_fit":0.75,"senior_general_fit":0.55,"mobility_friendly_fit":0.4,"stroller_fit":0.55,"one_day_fit":1,"same_day_flight_fit":0.1,"rain_fit":0.5,"value_for_money_fit":1,"iconic_landmark_fit":1,"cafe_fit":0.5,"food_fit":0.5,"nature_fit":1,"beach_fit":0.1,"nightlife_fit":0.1,"shopping_fit":0.25,"no_shopping_fit":1,"local_culture_fit":0.7,"storytelling_fit":0.9,"unesco_fit":0.55,"intangible_heritage_fit":0.5,"indoor_ratio":0.1,"weather_sensitivity":0.65,"comfort_level":0.55,"budget_fit":1,"premium_fit":0.2,"small_group_fit":0.15,"private_fit":0.05,"bus_fit":1,"price_band":"budget","pickup_base":"seoul_central","return_time_band":"19:00-19:30","duration_band":"13h","min_recommended_age":8,"hard_constraints":{"avoidIf":["mobility_limited","wheelchair_required"],"notIdealFor":["very_low_mobility","young_kids_under_6"]},"walking_notes":["13-hour day with ~4-5 km total walking.","Seoraksan paths rocky in places; Nami and Morning Calm flat.","Closed-toe shoes recommended.","Cable car at Seoraksan optional and not included."],"keywords":["seoul seoraksan day tour","nami island day trip","garden of morning calm tour","seoul winter wonder tour","seoraksan nami one day"],"synonym_hints":["seoul to seoraksan day tour","korea three signature stops day trip","seoul winter sonata tour"],"seasonality":"year_round","pickup_base_normalized":"seoul","vehicle_type_legacy":"bus_coach","anchor_poi_keys":["seoraksan_national_park","nami_island","garden_of_morning_calm"],"private_tour_fit":0.05,"customizable_route_fit":0.05,"flexibility_fit":0.2,"fixed_itinerary_fit":1,"national_park_fit":1,"buddhist_temple_fit":0.6,"k_drama_filming_fit":1,"winter_sonata_fit":1,"themed_garden_fit":1,"history_culture_fit":0.65,"religious_history_fit":0.45,"premium_dining_fit":0.15,"seasonal_fit":1,"winter_lighting_festival_fit":1,"autumn_foliage_fit":1,"china_mainland_market_fit":0.85,"korea_domestic_market_fit":0,"taiwan_market_fit":1,"singapore_market_fit":1,"hong_kong_market_fit":1,"china_diaspora_overseas_market_fit":1,"se_asia_market_fit":1,"us_market_fit":0.95,"europe_market_fit":0.95,"australia_market_fit":0.95,"japan_market_fit":1,"first_time_korea_fit":1,"seoul_day_trip_fit":1,"english_speaking_guide_provided":true,"chinese_speaking_guide_available_on_advance_notice":true,"japanese_speaking_guide_available_on_advance_notice":true},"matching_metadata":{"matching_schema":"match_tours_embedded_v2","embedded_for":"atockorea_tour_marketplace","primary_themes":["nature","scenic","national_park","k_drama_filming"],"secondary_themes":["buddhist_temple","themed_garden","hallyu_landmark","mountain"],"best_for":["first_time_korea","couples","solo_travelers","nature_lovers","photographers","k_drama_fans"],"not_recommended_for":["mobility_limited","very_young_children","shoppers","nightlife_seekers"],"source_of_truth_note":"Coach-tour combining Seoraksan + Nami Island + Garden of Morning Calm from Seoul. Attraction content reused from seoul-seoraksan-national-park-sokcho-beach-day-trip (Seoraksan) and seoul-private-nami-morning-calm-petite-france (Nami, Morning Calm). Sources: KTO VisitKorea, IUCN Green List, UNESCO, KNPS, Garden of Morning Calm official, Naminara Republic official, KBS Winter Sonata records, Wikipedia.","audit_summary":"Seoul-based 13-hour coach day trip on the classic Seoraksan + Nami + Morning Calm circuit. Direct equivalent on GetYourGuide market is the $82 ''From Seoul: Seoraksan, Nami Island, Garden of Morning Calm'' (t1137310)."}}'::jsonb
)
